-- =====================================================
-- (4) Who's-Who content_text repair.
--     The lesson 1n8wS0X... lost its body (stored a near-empty placeholder).
--     Restore the canonical body (3,244 chars, from
--     scripts/stage2-retag/artifacts/whos-who-body.txt). Dollar-quoted with a
--     tag that cannot appear in the body ($whoswho_body$). The length < 1000
--     guard makes this a no-op once repaired (idempotent).
-- =====================================================
UPDATE public.lessons
SET content_text = $whoswho_body$Who’s Who in the Food System
Summary: In this lesson, students will read and answer questions about four people who play important roles in the food system: a farm worker, a fast food worker, a line cook and a delivery person.
Objectives: Students will be able to identify and understand the role of different people that make the food system possible, including the struggles they face and the work they do to make the food system more just.
Cultural Responsiveness:  Encourages Learning in the Context of Culture. Promotes student-centered instruction. Reshapes Curriculum
Social-Emotional Skills: Relationship Skills. Social Awareness
Agenda/Class Flow:
Opening ritual: (10 minutes)
Give students a refresher on last class (Meet the Food System)
The last time we were together you all were introduced to the food system. Can anyone remind the class what a food system is or tell us any of the parts of the food system that you remember?
In today’s class we will be talking about the people and their role in the food system. We will be talking about their jobs  from start to finish and how everyone is important to making the system flow.
Ask students if any of their family members or have they ever worked in the food system, in other words, in any of these positions (cook/chef, delivery person, farmer, truck driver, cashier…)
Engaging activity: (30 minutes–20 minutes in groups, 10 minutes to share)
These jobs are just a small sample of the many people who work in our food system. All of these roles are important and make it possible for us to have food to eat. Now we are going to put ourselves in the shoes of the workers to understand what this very important job involves.
Students will work table groups to read stories about what a typical day of a food worker is like and answer questions about the workers.
Pick groups to share information about each of the workers.
Ask students if they know about cost of living in New York City. Share with them that minimum wage in NYC is $15/hour, which translates into about $1800/month,after taxes. Average rent for a studio apartment in NYC is $3478.
Closing ritual:
Have students share reflections about the activity. Ask the following questions:
What surprised you about these stories?
Did reading these stories change any ideas you already had about these jobs?
What are some ways you think these workers can be better supported?
Share a tasting and ask students
